SIMPLE: instrumental
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Instrumental
<hw>In`stru*men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>instrumental</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Acting as an instrument; serving as a means;
contributing to promote; conductive; helpful; serviceable; <as>as, he
was <ex>instrumental</ex> in conducting the business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The head is not more native to the heart,⟦br⟧
The hand more <qex>instrumental</qex> to the mouth.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, made by, or
prepared for, an instrument, esp. a musical instrument; <as>as,
<ex>instrumental</ex> music, distinguished from <ex>vocal</ex>
music</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He defended the use of <xex>instrumental</xex>
music in public worship.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sweet voices mix'd with <qex>instrumental</qex> sounds.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Applied to a case expressing
means or agency; <as>as, the <ex>instrumental</ex> case</as>. This is
found in Sanskrit and Russian as a separate case, but in Greek it was
merged into the dative, and in Latin into the ablative. In Old English
it was a separate case, but has disappeared, leaving only a few
anomalous forms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Instrumental errors</b></col>, <cd>those errors in
instrumental measurements, etc., which arise, exclusively from lack of
mathematical accuracy in an instrument.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instrumentalism</ent>⟦br⟧
